      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Property in a Flood Zone in Brisbane: What Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Flood overlay, disclosure obligations, buyer finance hurdles, and how to run a campaign that attracts the right buyers without underselling your property.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a Brisbane property that sits within a council flood overlay zone is not the barrier some sellers fear, but it does require a different level of preparation and a cleaner, more transparent approach to marketing. Buyers are better informed than ever, lenders run their own flood checks, and any attempt to obscure risk will surface at due diligence and damage your negotiating position. Getting ahead of the conversation is always the better strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Brisbane Council flood overlays work</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council maps flood risk through its online flood check tool and the City Plan flood overlay. Properties are categorised based on modelled flood levels at different return intervals: the 20-year, 100-year, and 500-year flood events. These are statistical probabilities, not predictions, but they determine how lenders assess risk and how insurers price coverage.</p>

      <p>A property can sit within a mapped overlay without having ever physically flooded. Conversely, some properties that flooded in 2011 or 2022 are not captured in council overlays because the flooding was stormwater-driven rather than riverine. Buyers and their conveyancers understand this distinction, and so should you when preparing to sell.</p>

      <p>Inner east Brisbane suburbs along Bulimba Creek, the Brisbane River corridor, and lower-lying pockets of Hawthorne, Morningside, Cannon Hill, and Norman Park have significant proportions of flood-affected stock. This is not unusual or disqualifying. Many of these properties have sold consistently for strong prices because the location and lifestyle advantages are real and buyers factor risk into their offers rather than walking away.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seller disclosure obligations in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland property law requires sellers to disclose material facts that would be relevant to a reasonable buyer's decision. Flood affectation is explicitly a material fact. Your agent is also obligated to disclose known flood risk. Attempting to withhold this information is not a strategy; it is a legal liability that can expose you to claims of misrepresentation after settlement.</p>

      <p>The Form 6 property disclosure statement includes a question about flood, drainage, and stormwater issues. If your property is within a council flood overlay or has a history of flooding, you answer honestly. The practical consequence of not doing so is a buyer who discovers the issue post-contract, potentially has grounds to pull out, and who certainly will not trust anything else you have told them.</p>

      <p>The 2022 Brisbane floods intensified buyer scrutiny of flood risk across the inner east. Buyers who were active in the market then remember it, and many now ask specifically about flood history and overlay status before they will even attend an open home. Being upfront in the marketing material rather than reactive in conversations with buyers saves time and produces better-qualified inquiry.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How flood risk affects buyer finance and insurance</h2>
      <p>Lenders carry out their own flood checks as part of the valuation process. A property in a high-risk overlay may attract a higher LVR restriction or a lower valuation, which can reduce the buyer's borrowing capacity. This is worth understanding before you set your price expectation, because it affects who can realistically buy your property and at what price.</p>

      <p>Insurance costs for flood-affected properties have increased significantly since 2022, and in some higher-risk zones, cover is harder to obtain or comes with flood exclusions. Buyers factor ongoing insurance costs into their total cost of ownership. A buyer whose insurance quote comes back at $6,000 per year for a property they were willing to pay $1.1 million for will revise their offer. Knowing this in advance allows you to price and negotiate accordingly rather than being surprised in late-stage negotiations.</p>

      <p>Some buyers specifically seek out overlay-affected properties because they understand the actual risk is lower than the mapped category suggests, or because they plan to undertake flood mitigation work. These buyers tend to be more decisive and less prone to collapsing at finance. Identifying them through targeted marketing is a more productive strategy than trying to attract buyers who will ultimately walk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing honestly without underselling</h2>
      <p>Transparent does not mean leading with the negative. A property near the river or creek has genuine advantages: views, green outlooks, proximity to parkland and cycling paths, and often a sense of space that is harder to find in the denser pockets of Brisbane's inner east. The marketing task is to present the complete picture, not to bury the flood information in small print or to ignore the location advantages in order to appear cautious.</p>

      <p>In practice this means including the flood check result in the contract of sale annexures from day one, making the council overlay category clear in the information memorandum or property report provided to buyers, and briefing your agent to discuss flood history confidently and accurately when buyers raise it at open homes. Buyers who are well-informed make better decisions, and better-informed buyers are more likely to proceed.</p>

      <p>Photography and property presentation still matter as much as they do for any other home. A flood-affected property that is beautifully presented, properly staged, and photographed well will attract stronger inquiry than one that is not. The overlay does not override the fundamentals of a good campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers typically ask and how to prepare your answers</h2>
      <p>At every open home for a flood-affected property, buyers will ask the same set of questions. Being prepared with accurate, detailed answers builds confidence and moves conversations forward. The questions are predictable: Did this property flood in 2011 or 2022? What is the council overlay category? What would insurance cost? Has any flood mitigation work been done? What is the floor level?</p>

      <p>The floor level is particularly useful. If your property has a floor height that sits above the modelled flood level for the 100-year event, that is worth knowing and communicating. A registered surveyor can provide this. It is a relatively small cost that can materially improve buyer confidence and, ultimately, your price.</p>

      <p>Receipts for any flood mitigation work, including raised electrical systems, sump pumps, or elevated storage, are worth gathering before you go to market. Buyers will ask. Having documentation ready accelerates due diligence and reduces the period during which a buyer can manufacture reasons to renegotiate.</p>

